article.description:
Alana Beard scored 22 points and Washington
beat the San Antonio Silver Stars 84-73 Wednesday night, the
Mystics' fourth straight win.
article.headline: Washington finishes with a 19-7 run
article.linkText: Mystics make it four in a row with win over Stars
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Fighting for a spot in the playoffs, the
Washington Mystics rallied from a 13-point deficit to defeat the
San Antonio Silver Stars on Wednesday night.

Alana Beard scored 22 points in an 84-73 victory, moving the
Mystics (16-16) into a second-place tie with Charlotte in the
Eastern Conference with their fourth straight win.

"It was a good win for our team," Washington coach Michael
Adams said. "Beard stepped it up for us tonight. She blocked
shots, had some great assists and even a steal. She's making us a
better team."

Nakia Sanford added 17 points and 11 rebounds for Washington,
while Coco Miller scored all 15 of her points in the second half to
key the Mystics' comeback.

With two games remaining in the regular season, the Mystics are
only one game behind first-place Connecticut. The top four teams in
each conference make the playoffs, and all six teams in the East
are still in contention.

"The win feels great," Beard said. "As far as my team goes, I
have complete confidence in our team. We all love and respect each
other and that just makes us a better team."

Adrienne Goodson and LaToya Thomas each had 20 for the Silver
Stars (8-25), who have lost 11 of 13. San Antonio was outscored
53-34 in the second half after leading 39-31 at the break.

"We can't let them score 53 points in a half," San Antonio
coach Shell Dailey said. "We didn't do a good job on defense in
the second half. You have to give it to them, they made a strong
push."

Goodson hit a jumper to give San Antonio a 66-65 lead with 5:23
left. Washington closed the game on a 19-7 run.

The Mystics took the lead for good at 67-66 on a jumper by
Miller with 5:05 to play. A three-point play by Beard with 1:13
remaining made it 77-68.

San Antonio could get no closer than nine points the rest of the
way.

"They are fighting for a playoff spot and we were in the way,"
said Thomas, who had 13 first-half points. "They came out in the
second half hot. They're a great team. They didn't miss shots."

Washington connected on 16-of-33 shots after intermission.

The Mystics close the season on the road at Phoenix on Friday
and New York on Sunday.
